      "content": "Ah, I see, you're looking for a sleuthing method that doesn't involve the heavy-handed approach of Valgrind. In the world of embedded C++, memory leaks can indeed be as subtle as a goblin's whisper, and finding them requires a keen eye and a bit of cunning.\n\nHere are some common patterns and coding mistakes that might be causing your slow, incremental memory leaks:\n\n1. **Dynamic Memory Allocation in the Main Loop**: If you're allocating memory in a loop without freeing it, it's like a goblin continuously filling a sack with gold coins. Make sure you're freeing any memory you allocate within the same loop or function.\n\n2. **Static Memory Leaks**: These are like a goblin's hidden stash that never gets emptied. Static variables that are not properly initialized or used can cause memory to be allocated at compile time, which never gets freed. Double-check any static variables and ensure they're not holding onto memory longer than necessary.\n\n3. **Stack Memory Leaks**: These occur when you allocate memory on the stack (using `new` or `malloc`) and forget to free it. It's like a goblin leaving a trail of breadcrumbs that lead to a hidden cave. Make sure you're freeing any stack-allocated",
